\begin_layout Title
Spectral Characteristics of Gravity-Capillary Waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Nathan J.
 M.
 Laxague,
 Christopher J.
 Zappa ,
 Deborah A.
 LeBel,
 and Michael L.
 Banner
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They measure slopes,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{y}$
\end_inset

 using a polarimetric camera,
 following Zappa's polarimetric slope sensing method.
 They tamper the bare data sequenece by a Tukey window.
 Then they compute the power spectrum
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S\left(k_{x},k_{y},\omega\right) & \propto\left|\mathcal{F}\left(s_{x}\right)\right|^{2}+\left|\mathcal{F}\left(s_{y}\right)\right|^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If I understood correctly,
 in fig.
 they present 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\infty}d\omega S\left(k_{x},k_{y},\omega\right)$
\end_inset

,
 so as to appreciate the total power per (directionally aware) wave vector.
 Note the 
\series bold
half
\series default
-plane integration.
 But since the Doppler shift + parasitic capillaries mess the dispersion,
 the logic here highly flawed.
 They claim that above 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.16cm^{-1}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $100rad/m$
\end_inset

,
 which is firmly in the short gravity wave regime) the power spectrum is unreliable - but this consists of most of the data presented in the figure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That being said,
 spatial resolution is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim4581rad/m$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim7.2cm^{-1}$
\end_inset

),
 and temporal resolution is 
\begin_inset Formula $30Hz$
\end_inset

.
 So as long as the power of waves near and higher than this frequency is negligible,
 and if there is 
\series bold
small advection 
\series default
(at 
\begin_inset Formula $k<2cm^{-1}$
\end_inset

,
 and since the dispersion is concave and frequency at 
\begin_inset Formula $2cm^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim60Hz$
\end_inset

,
 we need advection speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v<\sim30\frac{cm}{s}$
\end_inset

),
 one the setup should be able to get an honest appreciation of the 
\series bold
directional 
\series default
spatial spectrum.
 Otherwise one can always integrate over the angle to get an omnidirectional spectrum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They define the 
\series bold
dimensionless saturation spectrum 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}\left(k_{x},k_{y}\right):=k^{2}S$
\end_inset

 and its omnidirectional counterpart 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(k\right)=k\int_{\mathcal{S}\left(k\right)}d\theta\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They demarkate the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(112.7,1173\right)\frac{rad}{m}$
\end_inset

 where the two terms in the naive dispersion 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{2}=gk+\frac{\tau}{\rho}k^{3}$
\end_inset

 are less than 1 order of magnitude apart,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k=371\frac{rad}{m}$
\end_inset

 being the point of equal weight.
 They take 
\begin_inset Formula $g=9.81\frac{m}{s^{2}}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0.072\frac{N}{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=1030\frac{kg}{m^{3}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Technical analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Measuring height
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be the number of pixels,
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be physical the side length of the image,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta z$
\end_inset

 be the height sensitivity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}\equiv\frac{\Omega_{0}}{2\pi}$
\end_inset

 be the sampling rate and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 be the film duration.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(\omega,k_{x},k_{y}\right)$
\end_inset

 be the Fourier transform of the video.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After integrating over all directions and positive omegas,
 the power spectrum is 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(k\right)=\int_{+}d\omega\int_{S^{1}}kd\phi F\left(\omega,k,\phi\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I want to know how 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta z$
\end_inset

 correlates with the quality of the spectrum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{c}\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 is the coherence length of a particular wavenumber,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{c}\left(k\right)<L$
\end_inset

,
 then doubling
\series bold
 the frame length
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 sums this component incoherently.
 On the other hand,
 since the coherence length is usually above one wavelength,
 any component 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 than can be measured by the frame gets summed coherently at quadrupling the 
\series bold
pixel density 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\frac{N}{L^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 For components with 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{c}\left(k\right)>2L$
\end_inset

,
 the two changes gives a doubling (~
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

) improve in 
\begin_inset Formula $SNR$
\end_inset

.
 This improvement carries on until pixel side length is smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta z/\bar{s}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{s}$
\end_inset

 is some typical actual water slope,
 then the quantization noise in adjacent pixels becomes correlated and increasing pixel density does not improve 
\begin_inset Formula $SNR$
\end_inset

 either.
 This halt might also result if the pixel's side length reaches the overall height field correlation length 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(f\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

